The effect this has had is there is a long, truck-sized muddy puddle/pond (<meter away from these mushrooms) that holds enough water that it doesn’t ever dry out, even during the some of the driest seasons this place has seen in who knows how long. This occurrence is aided by the steep hillsides being almost entirely populated by very large, and equally as broad, Acer macrophyllum trees that reach out over the center to create an entire canopy of green that prevents any sunlight from entering this area for 4-5months of the year.
Anyway, my point is that it is a unique micro-climate created by an odd teamwork of glaciers and tractor-pulls.
The mushrooms do not root very far, sublignicolous; no sign of a veil, their stipes quickly bruise dark brown with ease.

Description:

Pileus: 20-60 mm; convex, then expanded, later with depressed center, sometimes with slight umbo; smooth, bald, slightly greasy to dry, a little bumpy; outer half decurved to incurved; outermost margin involute well into maturity, with very old specimens slightly sulcate; warm to bright orange brown, young with slightly paler margin, not hygrophanous.

Lamellae: Crowded, adnate, sometimes decurrent across the apex, often furcate; beige with orange tinge.

Spores: 6,1-7,7 × 4,6-7,5 µm; subglobose tot broadly ellipsoid, very small apiculus, with a depression just above apiculus; mostly spines and ridges, incomplete reticulum, upto 1,2 µm high.

Latex: White, later yellow; a bit bitter at first, later slightly acrid.

Stipe: 20-40 mm; flexuous, cilindrical to compressed, sometimes with more or less rounded base; dry, apex smooth, from here downward very finely rugulose; white basal mycelium which turns orange brown with time; concolourous with pileus.

Context: Brittle; paler than the exterior; soon hollow in the stipe.

Smell/Taste: Smell of the context is somewhat spicy, taste: see latex

Ecology: Solitary or in small troops scattered over the forest floor and well-decayed Birch wood, in a dried up fen, associated with Betula, Quercus and Populus.

results.notes:
Pileus: 30-50 mm, upto 40 mm high; ovoid at first with large, dull to depressed umbo, later campanulate with flattened center; first smooth, later finely granulose to scaly-fibrillose, granules/scales are easily wiped off, centrum remains smooth; (cretaceous) white with greyish brown center; surface smooth, non-striate; no discolouration after bruising; covered with droplets when young.

Lamellae: L: not recorded, l: 1-3; crowded, free from stipe, very narrow; margin finely fimbriate; white; no discolouration.

Stipe: Upto 70 mm; centrally placed, cilindrical to fusiform; entirely covered with fine flakes, giving the stipe a mat and pruinose appearance, easily wiped off, resulting in reddish brown discolouration; white with sometimes a slight reddish brown hue; fragile and fleeting annulus, smooth on top, very finely floccose on the underside, fimbriate margin; sometimes with wooly foot, often with small white bubils at the base, looking like primordia (in literature sometimes called “sclerotia”); covered in droplets when young or fresh.

Context: Very thin in the pileus, soon hollow in the stipe, dark line directly above the hymenium, dark cortex in the base, furthermore white with slight grey brown tinges in the base. Slowly brunnescent after cross section.

Smell/Taste: “Fresh”, almost a mix of mint, fruit and anise (?); inconspicuous taste, a bit musty with minor bitter tones.

Ecology: Woodchip path of a dog walking area, probably broadleaf chips, since the mycelium of Chlorocibora spec. is everywhere, with Salix spec. standing in the vicinity. Sharing the habitat with Agrocybe rivulosa.

Comment: Lobaria pulmonaria is very beautiful and one of the largest lichens of Slovenia. It is the most beautiful after a few rainy days. Then dry it is brownish or dull green, but when moist it becomes shiny green. Since it is very sensitive to air pollution it is in sharp decline in Europe and hence protected in many countries. As such it is used as an indicator of rich, healthy and undisturbed ecosystems.

Lobaria pulmonaria can be quite common in its ideal habitat; however, actually it is quite a rare find nowadays, particularly in low-land industrial countries. It occurs most often in shady environments. Green algae give Lobaria pulmonaria its bright green appearance. The underside of this lichen is whitish with pockets of cyanobacteria (blue-green algae). Hence this species is an association of three much different living beings: fungus and two kinds of algae.

Its main method of reproducing is by tiny granule-like isidia or soredia, which develop on the edges of its talus (Fig. 63), eventually break off and fall on ground or in crevices of three bank, where they can grow into new lichen. Sometimes Lobaria pulmonaria also has spore-producing structures called apothecia that spread fungal spores. But apothecia are very rarely observed.

Circumscription:
Medium sized Inkcap with remarkably white-grey pileus and recurving, filamentose-floccose velum remnants which lie loosely on the pileus, growing in a cavity of a trunk of a cut-down Fagus (Beech). A very rare species in the Netherlands, listed as Critically Endangered on the Red List of 2008 (Arnolds & Veerkamp, 2008).

Description:

Pileus: 13×15 mm; campanulate, sulcate; covered with large, white, filamentose-floccose velum remnants, which lie loosely on the pileus; white-grey with slightly browner centre, darker grey towards the margin.

Lamellae: Numerous, crowded, fairly broad when young; first pale, then grey, later black, with grey floccose margin when young; deliquescent.

Stipe: 70×3-4 mm; cylindrical, flexuous, slightly tapering towards the top, entirely covered with fine erect fibrils, sericeous underneath; white.

Context: Thin, clear division of pileal and stipe context; white, darker in the foot and around the centre at the apex; hollow in the stipe.

Smell/Taste: Smells mushroomy, no taste recorded.

Microscopy: Spores av. 9,18×6,12 µm; very broadly fusiform to amygdaliform met acute apex; chocolate brown, hyaline; Basidia: 4-sterigmate; Pleurocystidia: 70 µm, ellipsoid-ovoid, scarce, hyaline; Cheilocystidia: not measured, globose to ellipsoid-ovoid, hyaline; Velum: long chains of sausage-shaped cells, sometimes bloated, sometimes branched with sporadically fine encrustation.

Ecology: Solitary in the heart of a stump of Fagus (Beech), lignicole, mesotrophic sandy soil.
